INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '9b084a45-6c85-4f2a-b152-887987fb64de',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$grafana_de — Replicating Tableau LOD Expressions and Calculated Fields Without Leaving Grafana$escape$,
  $escape$Grafana's Transformations panel is your calculated field engine. The 'Add field from calculation' transform executes binary operations across series post-query — equivalent to Tableau's row-level calculated fields. Chain 'Reduce' transforms before it to collapse series dimensionality before computing ratios or deltas.

For Tableau's FIXED LOD equivalent, push the aggregation into the SQL panel query itself using window functions — Grafana has no native LOD layer, so server-side SQL is the correct boundary. Use OVER() with PARTITION BY to fix a dimension regardless of what dashboard variables inject into the WHERE clause. Wrap that in a subquery if you need to join it back to filtered data.

Dashboard design: use Grafana's panel repeat (variable-driven) to tile breakdowns the way Tableau uses containers. For performance, keep transformation chains under 4 steps and always align queries to $__interval to reduce returned data points before any client-side transform runs. High-cardinality labels (>10k series) should aggregate in the data source, never in the Grafana transformation layer.$escape$,
  $escape$-- FIXED LOD equivalent in a Grafana SQL panel
-- Revenue share per region, unaffected by time-filter variable
SELECT
  region,
  SUM(revenue)                              AS region_revenue,
  SUM(revenue) / SUM(SUM(revenue)) OVER () AS pct_of_total,
  COUNT(DISTINCT order_id)                  AS order_count
FROM sales
WHERE $__timeFilter(created_at)  -- Grafana macro injects time range
GROUP BY region
ORDER BY region_revenue DESC;$escape$,
