INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'c6533441-c2f7-4e14-9d87-96fe2ff96d72',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Grafana_de Users: Apache Superset's SQL Lab, Native Filters & RLS Decoded$escape$,
  $escape$Coming from Grafana to Apache Superset requires remapping core primitives. Superset's Datasets are not data sources — they're SQL-backed virtual tables registered against a database connection, with column-level metadata (filterable, groupable flags) stored in Superset's own metadata DB. Unlike Grafana's data source abstraction, every chart must bind to a dataset, making query governance explicit.

SQL Lab is Superset's ad-hoc environment — closer to Grafana Explore, but with persistent query history and the ability to promote results directly into a Chart without rewriting SQL. Results export as datasets, closing the Explore-to-dashboard loop Grafana lacks natively.

Native Filters replace Grafana dashboard variables but with cross-dataset fan-out. A single filter propagates to multiple charts via `filter_scopes` config — no per-panel `$variable` templating required.

For security, Superset's Row Level Security (RLS) appends WHERE clauses per role/dataset pair — more granular than Grafana's connection-level permissions. A single dataset can serve multiple tenants without duplicating data sources. Chart types are declared via the VizPlugin API: `buildQueryContext` returns a `QueryObject` array, making backend query logic explicit and testable.$escape$,
  $escape$# Create an RLS rule via Superset REST API
# Equivalent to Grafana per-datasource user scoping, but at row level
curl -X POST "https://superset.example.com/api/v1/rowlevelsecurity/" \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $SUPERSET_TOKEN" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{
    "name": "tenant_isolation",
    "tables": [42],
    "roles": [3],
    "clause": "tenant_id = {{current_user_id()}}",
    "filter_type": "Regular"
  }'$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
