INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '63057c58-c84d-4686-80df-cdfb1e44f4e3',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Grafana Self-Serve Analytics — Guardrails with RBAC, Chained Variables, and Library Panels$escape$,
  $escape$Grafana's self-serve story hinges on three layers working together. First, RBAC: assign non-technical users the `Viewer` role at the folder level—not the Org level—so they can't touch dashboards outside their scope. Disable Explore access org-wide via `grafana.ini` (`[explore] enabled = false`) to prevent raw query exposure against prod data sources.

Second, use chained template variables as guardrails. A top-level `$team` variable (query type, hidden) pre-filters every subsequent variable—`$service`, `$environment`—so users only see data scoped to their context. Set the chained variables to `Multi-value = false` to prevent combinatorial blowup on heavy queries.

Third, treat Grafana Library Panels as your semantic layer. Encode metric definitions—p99 latency, error rate formula, SLO burn rate—once in a Library Panel. Non-technical users consume these panels without touching PromQL. When the definition changes, update the Library Panel and all dependent dashboards inherit it instantly. Pair this with provisioned dashboards (`allow_ui_updates = false`) to prevent accidental edits drifting from the canonical definition.$escape$,
  $escape$# grafana.ini — lock down self-serve surface area
[explore]
enabled = false

[auth]
disable_login_form = false

# provisioning/dashboards/team-analytics.yaml
apiVersion: 1
providers:
  - name: team-analytics
    folder: Self-Serve
    disableDeletion: true
    allowUiUpdates: false
    options:
      path: /etc/grafana/dashboards/team$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
